1
00:00:15,500 --> 00:00:20,800
I'm Mario, I built Pi in a world of slop, and this is a tragedy in three acts.

2
00:00:21,200 --> 00:00:28,800
Just to talk about this real quick, a bunch of people on the internet gave me money for ad space on my torso, and all of that goes to a charity, so yeah, thanks guys.

3
00:00:29,800 --> 00:00:31,400
So, act one, building Pi.

4
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:34,000
In the beginning there was cloud code and it was good, right?

5
00:00:34,300 --> 00:00:39,000
We all got basically catnipped by that thing and stopped sleeping.

6
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:45,300
A bunch of stuff before that, but Cloud Code was the one thing that kind of clicked with me the most.

7
00:00:45,800 --> 00:00:48,600
And to preface all of this, I love the Cloud team.

8
00:00:48,700 --> 00:00:51,400
They're brilliant people, talented, super high velocity.

9
00:00:51,400 --> 00:00:54,200
So they also created the entire game.

10
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:55,900
Major props to them.

11
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:56,900
So this is not a roast.

12
00:00:56,900 --> 00:01:01,200
This is just me, an old man, telling you why I stopped using Cloud Code and built my own thing.

13
00:01:02,700 --> 00:01:10,900
In 2025, I started using Cloud Code in about April, I think, thanks to Peter, because he told us the agents are working now.

14
00:01:12,200 --> 00:01:15,100
And back then, it was simple and predictable and fit my workflow.

15
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:15,900
But eventually,

16
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:24,300
The token madness got hold of them, I think, and the team got bigger and they started dogfooding that stuff and built a lot of features.

17
00:01:24,400 --> 00:01:27,300
A lot of features I don't need, which is fine, I can just ignore them.

18
00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:30,000
But with velocity and more features come...

19
00:01:30,700 --> 00:01:36,800
And that's bad because I used to work at construction sites and if my hammer breaks every day, I'm getting really mad.

20
00:01:36,900 --> 00:01:40,000
And if my development tools break every day, I'm also getting mad.

21
00:01:40,800 --> 00:01:41,500
So there was this.

22
00:01:41,800 --> 00:01:42,800
It's just a running gag.

23
00:01:42,800 --> 00:01:45,400
And here's Tarek telling us that Cloud Code is now a game engine.

24
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:47,900
And here's Mitchell from Ghosty telling us, no, it's not.

25
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:51,100
And eventually they fixed the flicker, but then other stuff broke.

26
00:01:51,100 --> 00:01:54,800
And I think they're now in the third iteration of a 2E renderer.

27
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:57,000
Yeah, but that's just a symptom.

28
00:01:57,100 --> 00:02:00,200
The real problem is that my context wasn't my context.

29
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:02,900
Cloud code is the thing that controls my context.

30
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:07,500
And behind my back, cloud code does things to the context.

31
00:02:07,800 --> 00:02:11,800
So you have the system problem, which changes on every release, including the tool definitions.

32
00:02:11,800 --> 00:02:14,200
They would remove tools, modify tools.

33
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:15,300
It's not good.

34
00:02:15,900 --> 00:02:22,500
They would insert system reminders in the most inopportune place in your context, telling the model, here's some information.

35
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:25,400
It may or may not be relevant to what you're doing.

36
00:02:26,200 --> 00:02:28,600
It actually says it may or may not be relevant what you're doing.

37
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:31,800
And that kind of confused the model, and that kind of broke my workflows.

38
00:02:34,100 --> 00:02:40,200
On top of all that, there's zero observability because that's how the tool is constructed and I like knowing what my agents are doing.

39
00:02:40,600 --> 00:02:42,300
There's zero model choice, which is obvious.

40
00:02:42,300 --> 00:02:46,900
It's the native anthropic harness, so it makes sense for them to want you to use cloth, right?

41
00:02:47,800 --> 00:02:56,300
And there's almost zero extensibility, and some of you might have written some hooks for Cloud Code, but I'm telling you the number of hooks and the depth of those hooks is very shallow.

42
00:02:57,200 --> 00:03:00,000
And every time a hook triggers, what actually happens is a new problem.

43
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:06,300
processes get spawned, basically the command you specified for the hook to be executed, and I don't find that specifically efficient.

44
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:16,600
So I took a step back and looked around for alternatives, and I'd like to especially call out AMP and FactoryDroid, the Porsche and Lamborghini of coding agent harnesses.

45
00:03:16,600 --> 00:03:18,200
So if you can afford them, please use them.

46
00:03:18,200 --> 00:03:19,000
They're at the frontier.

47
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:21,100
They're really good, and the teams are fantastic.

48
00:03:21,600 --> 00:03:22,800
And there's a bunch of other options.

49
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:26,900
And I have history in OSS, so naturally I kind of gravitated towards open code.

50
00:03:27,300 --> 00:03:35,600
And again, brilliant team, super high execution velocity, and they don't sell you hype, they sell you tools that work for the most part.

51
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:42,400
I started looking under the hood of open code with respect to context handling as well, because that's the most important part for me.

52
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:44,100
And I found a bunch of things like...

53
00:03:44,500 --> 00:03:53,200
Given some conditions, OpenCode would just prune tool output after a specific minimum amount of tokens.

54
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:55,300
And that basically lobotomizes the model.

55
00:03:56,500 --> 00:04:04,100
There's also LSP server support, which means every time your model is calling the edit tool, OpenCode goes to the LSP server that's connected.

56
00:04:04,700 --> 00:04:06,000
asks, are there any errors?

57
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:09,500
And if so, injects that as part of the edit tool result.

58
00:04:10,200 --> 00:04:13,300
Which is bad, because think about how you edit code.

59
00:04:13,500 --> 00:04:18,000
You're not writing a line of code, checking the errors, writing the next line, checking the errors.

60
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:18,800
You don't do that.

61
00:04:19,100 --> 00:04:21,100
You finish your work, and then you check the errors.

62
00:04:21,500 --> 00:04:22,600
This confuses the model.

63
00:04:23,100 --> 00:04:27,500
There's a bunch of other things like storing individual messages of a session in a JSON file.

64
00:04:27,800 --> 00:04:29,900
Each message is a JSON file on disk.

65
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:42,100
There was this, and this happens to all of us, no blame there, but it's not great if by default a server spins up, course headers are set in such a way that any website you open in your browser can now access your open code server.

66
00:04:44,500 --> 00:04:53,600
And entirely unrelated to all of this, I started looking into benchmarks for coding agent harnesses and found Terminal Bench, which is a pretty good benchmark, all things considered.

67
00:04:54,300 --> 00:04:58,500
And the funny part about it is that it's the most minimal kind of thing you can think of.

68
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:05,700
All it gives the model is a tool to send keystrokes to a TMAX session and read the output of that TMAX session.

69
00:05:06,100 --> 00:05:09,900
There's no file tools, no subagents, none of that stuff.

70
00:05:10,600 --> 00:05:13,000
And it's one of the best performing harnesses in the leaderboard.

71
00:05:13,600 --> 00:05:16,000
Here's the leaderboard from December 2025.

72
00:05:16,900 --> 00:05:23,700
Irrespective of model family, Terminus scores higher, mostly even higher than the native harness of that model.

73
00:05:24,200 --> 00:05:25,300
So what does that tell us?

74
00:05:25,900 --> 00:05:32,600
A form 2 thesis is, we are in the fuck around and find out phase of coding agents, and the current form is not their final form, right?

75
00:05:33,600 --> 00:05:37,400
So, second thesis is we need better ways to fuck around.

76
00:05:37,500 --> 00:05:41,100
And for me that means self-modifying malleable agents.

77
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:46,400
Things that the agent itself can modify and I can modify depending on my workflow.

78
00:05:46,900 --> 00:05:53,900
So I stripped away all the things, built a minimal core, but made it super extensible and made it so that the agent can modify itself.

79
00:05:55,300 --> 00:05:56,400
With some creature comforts.

80
00:05:56,600 --> 00:05:57,800
It's not entirely bare bones.

81
00:05:58,400 --> 00:05:59,000
So that's Pi.

82
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:00,000
It's an agent that

83
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,100
adapts to your workflow instead of the other way around.

84
00:06:02,700 --> 00:06:15,400
It comes with four packages, an AI package, it's basically just an abstraction across providers and context handoff between providers, an agent core, which is just a while loop and a tool calling, bespoke to a framework.

85
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:20,900
I come out of game development, so I built a thing that actually doesn't flicker too much, and the coding agent itself.

86
00:06:21,100 --> 00:06:22,400
Here's Pi's system prompt.

87
00:06:23,900 --> 00:06:24,300
That's it.

88
00:06:25,400 --> 00:06:29,700
Eventually, the industry created a new standard called skills, which is basically just markdown files.

89
00:06:30,200 --> 00:06:32,500
So we added that as well, and that needs to go in a system prompt.

90
00:06:32,500 --> 00:06:35,600
So begrudgingly, we had to add a couple more lines.

91
00:06:36,100 --> 00:06:39,600
And finally, here's the magic that makes Py able to modify itself.

92
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:47,300
We shipped the documentation, which was handcrafted by me and an agent, and code examples of extensions.

93
00:06:48,100 --> 00:06:56,800
And all we need to do for the agent to modify itself is tell it, here's the documentation, here's some code that shows you how to modify yourself by writing extensions.

94
00:06:57,900 --> 00:06:58,900
It comes with four tools.

95
00:06:58,900 --> 00:06:59,500
That's all it has.

96
00:06:59,600 --> 00:07:00,500
Read, write, edit, bash.

97
00:07:00,700 --> 00:07:01,900
Here's the tool definitions.

98
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:04,000
Don't read the text, just look at the size.

99
00:07:05,900 --> 00:07:06,200
That's it.

100
00:07:06,900 --> 00:07:09,700
Here's what happens when you start a new session in one of these tools.

101
00:07:11,500 --> 00:07:20,800
So the thing is, the models are actually reinforcement trained up the wazoo, so they know what a coding agent is, because a coding agent harness is basically what they're being trained when they are post-trained.

102
00:07:21,300 --> 00:07:24,300
You don't need 10,000 tokens to tell them you're a coding agent.

103
00:07:24,500 --> 00:07:26,700
They know, because they are coding agents now.

104
00:07:27,900 --> 00:07:30,400
Pi is also a yellow by default because my security

105
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:40,900
Security needs are different than yours, and I don't think a little dialogue that pops up every time you call Bash asking you to approve is a smart security mechanism.

106
00:07:41,200 --> 00:07:48,100
So instead, I give you so much rope that you can build anything that's fit for your specific security needs.

107
00:07:48,900 --> 00:07:50,400
There's also stuff that's not built in.

108
00:07:51,500 --> 00:07:54,600
I'm a heathen, because this is how I do it.

109
00:07:55,800 --> 00:08:01,600
But if you don't like that, then you just ask Pi to build you sub-agent support on plan mode or MCP support, whatever you need.

110
00:08:02,900 --> 00:08:07,300
Extensibility comes with a bunch of table stakes, and then with the extensions itself.

111
00:08:07,400 --> 00:08:09,700
And extensions in Pi are just TypeScript modules.

112
00:08:10,100 --> 00:08:12,100
In the simplest case, a TypeScript file on disk.

113
00:08:12,500 --> 00:08:13,700
You point Pi at that.

114
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:16,200
Here's an extension loaded as part of the harness.

115
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:25,400
And with that, you get basically an extension API that lets you hook into everything and define stuff for the harness to expose to the model.

116
00:08:25,700 --> 00:08:28,400
And that includes tools, slash command shortcuts.

117
00:08:28,700 --> 00:08:34,300
You can listen in on any kind of event and react and then save state in the session.

118
00:08:36,100 --> 00:08:43,100
Optionally provided to the agent as well or stored there for tools that analyze sessions as part of the organizational workflows.

119
00:08:43,500 --> 00:08:46,900
You can do custom compaction, custom providers, and you have full control over the tools.

120
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:48,500
So you can modify everything in Py.

121
00:08:49,400 --> 00:08:59,400
And you can then bundle all of that up and put it on NPM or on GitHub because I think we don't need to reinvent another bunch of silos called marketplaces.

122
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:01,900
They have package managers.

123
00:09:02,900 --> 00:09:04,100
And all of that hot reloads.

124
00:09:04,200 --> 00:09:16,600
So if you develop an extension for Pi, you do so in the session, and you hot reload the changes and see the effects of that immediately, which is very great, and it's also game development thingies.

125
00:09:16,900 --> 00:09:18,600
In game development, you want high...

126
00:09:18,900 --> 00:09:21,100
Very low iteration speeds.

127
00:09:21,500 --> 00:09:22,100
And that's great.

128
00:09:22,600 --> 00:09:23,600
So a couple of examples.

129
00:09:24,100 --> 00:09:29,100
Cloud or Anthropic ships the slash by the way, which lets you talk to the agent while it goes on its main quest.

130
00:09:29,500 --> 00:09:35,000
I posted this little prompt on Twitter, jokingly, and somebody built it in five minutes with more features.

131
00:09:35,300 --> 00:09:37,400
And it didn't have to fork or clone Pi.

132
00:09:37,500 --> 00:09:39,100
It just let the agent write.

133
00:09:39,500 --> 00:09:41,100
The extension based on the prompt.

134
00:09:42,100 --> 00:09:45,100
Here's Nico, he's one of the most prolific extension writers.

135
00:09:45,200 --> 00:09:46,900
I don't know what the fuck is going on here.

136
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:50,000
It's a chat room for all of his Pi agents and they talk with each other.

137
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:53,000
I would never use this, but all of this is custom, including the UI.

138
00:09:53,700 --> 00:09:55,100
Or you can play NES games.

139
00:09:55,800 --> 00:09:56,700
Or you can play Doom.

140
00:09:58,700 --> 00:10:01,000
And there's a bunch of other examples I'm not going to talk about.

141
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:02,600
So how do you build a Py extension?

142
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:03,100
You don't.

143
00:10:03,300 --> 00:10:09,600
You tell Py to build it for you based on your specifications, and then you just iterate with it on that and hot reload during the session.

144
00:10:10,400 --> 00:10:11,800
I'm going to skip that example as well.

145
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:16,400
And if you don't like building things yourself, and I hope you do like building things yourself, but if you don't,

146
00:10:17,300 --> 00:10:24,300
You can look on MPM or our little search interface on top of MPM to find packages for subagents, MCP, and so on.

147
00:10:24,400 --> 00:10:25,400
So does it actually work?

148
00:10:25,700 --> 00:10:29,900
Well, here's the terminal bench leaderboard from October before Pi had compaction.

149
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:31,900
I added that for Peter's claw thingy.

150
00:10:32,500 --> 00:10:33,500
It scored sixth place.

151
00:10:35,700 --> 00:10:37,100
But none of this is actually about Pi.

152
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:41,300
I basically want you to retake control of your tools and workflows.

153
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:42,100
So build your own.

154
00:10:43,200 --> 00:10:46,300
And if you want to know more about Pi and OpenClaw, go to this talk, please.

155
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:48,100
Yeah, and then eventually Peter happened.

156
00:10:48,400 --> 00:10:57,300
He put Pi inside of OpenClaw, so it's a Gentic core, which meant my open source project became the target of a lot of OpenClaw instances, unbeknownst to their users.

157
00:10:57,800 --> 00:10:59,900
So this is Act 2, OSS in the Age of Clankers.

158
00:11:00,400 --> 00:11:01,500
Clankers are destroying OSS.

159
00:11:01,600 --> 00:11:02,300
Here's Teal Draw.

160
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:04,400
They closed down the issue on pull request tracker.

161
00:11:04,800 --> 00:11:07,100
Here's OpenClaw's trackers.

162
00:11:07,500 --> 00:11:08,000
Here's mine.

163
00:11:08,300 --> 00:11:11,000
Half of that is OpenClaw instances who post garbage.

164
00:11:11,900 --> 00:11:13,600
So I started to rage against the clankers.

165
00:11:15,300 --> 00:11:23,500
If you send a pull request, it gets autoclosed with a comment that asks you to please write a nice issue in your human voice no longer than a screen worth of text.

166
00:11:23,900 --> 00:11:30,900
And if I see that, I write, looks good to me, and your account name gets put in a file in the repository, and the next time you send a pull request, it's let through.

167
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:33,800
Clankers don't read that comment.

168
00:11:33,800 --> 00:11:35,800
They don't go back once they've posted a pull request.

169
00:11:35,900 --> 00:11:36,900
So that's a perfect filter.

170
00:11:37,700 --> 00:11:39,300
Mitchell eventually turned it into Vouch.

171
00:11:39,800 --> 00:11:40,500
Here's a clanker.

172
00:11:41,100 --> 00:11:42,000
I also labeled them.

173
00:11:42,100 --> 00:11:45,900
If you had interactions with OpenClaw, your issues get deprioritized.

174
00:11:46,200 --> 00:11:52,700
I also built tools where I embed issues and pull request texts into 3D space, so I see clusters of issues.

175
00:11:53,400 --> 00:11:55,000
I also invented OSS vacation.

176
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:58,200
I just close the tracker whenever I want, so I have my life back.

177
00:11:59,000 --> 00:11:59,700
So does this work?

178
00:11:59,800 --> 00:12:00,000
Yes.

179
00:12:00,200 --> 00:12:00,500
Sort of.

180
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:05,100
Which leads me to act three, slow the fuck down.

181
00:12:05,900 --> 00:12:06,900
Everything's broken.

182
00:12:09,100 --> 00:12:12,600
And then there's people that say, our product's been 100% built by agents.

183
00:12:12,700 --> 00:12:13,200
Yes, we know.

184
00:12:13,200 --> 00:12:14,200
It fucking sucks now.

185
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:15,200
Congratulations.

186
00:12:22,800 --> 00:12:26,200
And I'm hearing this from my peers, and this is entirely unhealthy.

187
00:12:27,700 --> 00:12:30,900
So here's how we should not work with agents and why, at least in my opinion.

188
00:12:31,200 --> 00:12:39,600
I wrote this on my blog a while ago, but the basic gist is, we're having an army of agents, and you're using Beats, and you don't know that it's basically uninstallable malware.

189
00:12:39,800 --> 00:12:41,300
And Anthropic built a C compiler.

190
00:12:41,400 --> 00:12:43,100
It kind of works, but actually doesn't.

191
00:12:43,100 --> 00:12:45,300
And we're hoping the next generation of models will fix it.

192
00:12:45,300 --> 00:12:48,400
And here is Curso building a browser, and that's also super fucking broken.

193
00:12:48,900 --> 00:12:50,200
But the next generation will fix it.

194
00:12:50,500 --> 00:12:51,700
And SaaS is dead.

195
00:12:51,700 --> 00:12:52,900
Software is solved in six months.

196
00:12:52,900 --> 00:12:55,900
And my grandma just built herself a Spotify with her open claw.

197
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:57,600
Come on, people.

198
00:12:58,900 --> 00:13:05,800
So agents are actually compounding boo-boos, which is my word for errors, with zero learning and no bottlenecks and delayed pain.

199
00:13:05,900 --> 00:13:07,000
The delayed pain is for you.

200
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:12,000
Here's your code base on a human, on one agent, and 10 agents.

201
00:13:12,400 --> 00:13:14,100
How much of the agent code can you review?

202
00:13:14,900 --> 00:13:18,500
Here's the same code base, but expressed in number of boo-boos per day.

203
00:13:19,900 --> 00:13:21,800
How much of those boo-boos do you think you'll find?

204
00:13:22,400 --> 00:13:24,300
Then you say, oh, I have a review agent.

205
00:13:25,100 --> 00:13:27,500
Let me introduce you to the wonderful world of the Ouroboros.

206
00:13:28,300 --> 00:13:28,900
Doesn't work.

207
00:13:29,100 --> 00:13:30,100
It catches some issues.

208
00:13:31,100 --> 00:13:33,400
The problem is that agents and merchants have learned complexity.

209
00:13:33,700 --> 00:13:35,400
Where did they learn that complexity from?

210
00:13:35,600 --> 00:13:36,300
From the internet.

211
00:13:36,400 --> 00:13:37,200
What's on the internet?

212
00:13:37,400 --> 00:13:38,600
All our old garbage code.

213
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:45,100
There are some pearls on the internet, really well-designed systems, but 90% of code on the internet is our old garbage.

214
00:13:45,300 --> 00:13:46,600
That's what the models learned from.

215
00:13:47,600 --> 00:13:58,100
And every decision of an agent is local, especially if the code base is so big that it doesn't fit into its context, and if you let it go wild and add abstractions everywhere that are intertwined.

216
00:13:59,200 --> 00:14:03,700
So that leads to lots of abstractions and duplication and backwards compatibility.

217
00:14:03,700 --> 00:14:05,900
Who has seen that in the output of their agent?

218
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:07,000
It's fucking annoying.

219
00:14:07,400 --> 00:14:08,800
Or defense in depth.

220
00:14:09,400 --> 00:14:14,800
So yeah, you get enterprise-grade complexity within two weeks with just two humans and ten agents.

221
